d Kingdom","Beaminster, Dorset, England":"Beaminster, Dorset, England","Stowell, Somerset, England":"Stowell, Somerset, England","Seaborough, Dorset, England":"Seaborough, Somerset, England","East Down, Devon, England":"East Down, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Appleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places in all parts of England named Appleton, from Old English <i>æppeltūn</i> ‘orchard’ (literally ‘apple enclosure’). Apples were particularly important in the Middle Ages as a food for survival through the winter.","History: This surname was brought to North America in 1635 by Samuel Appleton, who migrated from Ipswich, England, to Ipswich, MA."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Appleton was born in 1482, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, her father, Robert Appleton, was 32 and her mother, Christiana Gould, was 28. She married George Pyne before 1509. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in 1548, in East Down, Devon, England, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1482–1548":"1482–1548","1472–1525":"1472–1525","1478–Female":"1478–Surnud","–1530":"–1530","1509–1574":"1509–1574","1511–Male":"1511–Surnud","1513–1565":"1513–1565","1450–1491":"1450–1491","1454–1500":"1454–1500","5 May 1500":"5. mai 1500","before 1509":"enne 1509","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","1482":"1482","1491":"1491","20 July 1530":"20. juuli 1530","1525":"1525","1513":"1513","1500":"1500","1511":"1511","1478":"1478","1565":"1565","1454":"1454","1574":"1574","1530":"1530","about 1513":"umbes 1513","about 1511":"umbes 1511","1509":"1509","1548":"1548","Somersetshire, England":"Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Beaminster, Dorset, Engla